social_posts.post_text: I’m in REHAB—a course of treatment for certain abuses. Each day is a new journey. Taking one day off means I run the risk of relapse. I can’t go back. No more self-sabotage. Forward is the way.

I thought I knew the world and all it had to offer. I thought I knew myself and all I had to give. I thought I knew God, but my understanding wasn’t even close to reality. Then, life happened and I quickly found out that I didn’t know crap! I’ve found it difficult to sit in different settings where compassion and grace aren’t the foremost objectives. I’m more comfortable with the rejects and “failures” than I am with the “cool” kids. I enjoy the company of outsiders. The need to perform for others is beyond me. I’ve learned to enjoy my reality and embrace my pain. In fact, it’s brought me closer to God. It empties me of pride and ego. At my lowest, I have nothing of value to give to anyone, and it’s that place that I find strength because I can only rely on God. Now, in my consciousness, I see my struggle to be self-righteous and retain a faux power that’s absent of heavenly intervention. I thought I knew God, but I didn’t know crap! It was always me, and it’s always been me. I see my struggle with God into the dark hours of the night, and I understand the need to break me to end my fighting. It’s in this brokenness that I’ve found healing, identity, hope and joy and escaped the grasp of depression and suicidal thoughts. I’ve entered my second half of life, and it’s refreshing. It makes me look at the first half and question why it took so long. It all happened for a reason, and I’m thankful for every experience. But, I’m glad the first half is over. The sun rises on this day bringing with it a hope I’ve never known or seen before. And, it’s in my solitude and breaking away from what was that has allowed me to accept what is. Selah. 🤟🏾.
You’ll know when you get there. Keep going. 🤟🏾.

I can be a time traveler. It’s one who has anxiety about the future while being tormented by the thoughts/events of the past. It’s one who finds it difficult to live in the present. I tend to drift to one side or the other. But, I’m learning how to get God to my heart before my thoughts get there. It’s the only way that truly works and stops the time traveler syndrome. I guess. I don’t know. Honestly, I’m living on borrowed strength right now because I’m emptied of my own. And, this is the strongest I’ve ever been because it’s the weakest I’ve ever been. Selah. 🤟🏾.

Find your inspiration. Formulate your strategy. Then, remain consistent. It doesn’t take much to be exceptional in a society that celebrates mediocrity and doesn’t challenge procrastination. The extra mile isn’t packed. Everyone is on the express way trying to get to their destination quickly. Stay the course even if it’s difficult and slower. Read daily. Mind your business. Refuse to gossip. Speak kindly to yourself and edify others. Be of service to others. Spend time with people who make you better. Forgive yourself and others. Learn a new trade. Enjoy your hobbies unapologetically. Develop an understanding of God that isn’t buried under legalism and performance. And, challenge yourself to be better.  Oh yeah, and have fun. Smile and laugh often. 🤟🏾.
And, only provide an apology and/or explanation to those who need it. 🤟🏾

Someone asked me this question, and I felt it important enough share. Sadly, much of our Christian journey is filled with shame and inadequacy. At least mine was. It was all about what I’m not doing and the need to do more. The fight in the soul is…when is it ever enough? It’s for this reason we feel like God is never satisfied with us, so many of us quit trying altogether. Why strive for such an unattainable goal that’s interpreted by man therefore the goalposts change constantly with each passing generation, more and more laws are added for us to live up to. We’ve made salvation more confusing, and we’ve placed more restrictions on Heaven than God. Our theology is so heady now. We love to get in God’s way. The truth is we don’t have faith in Him; we have faith in the idea of Him. If we truly trusted Him then it would be by His ability and will, not ours. But that’s too simple for us. We crave difficult and shame. It’s not enough to just believe in God. We have to do His job too. That’s all. Thanks for coming to my TED Talk. Selah, shawty. 🤟🏾

While conversing with a brother today, he sent these words that spoke loudly. The context of our conversation was specific to the plight of “angry black men” although we don’t believe it’s fully limited to just one group of men. Nonetheless, it would seem that we’re constantly trying to get others to understand our background and culture so they can relate to our experience and pain. Some of us choose to conform to be liked and accepted rather than retain their dignity and difference. For those of us who don’t, we’re “gifted” understanding as long as we can temper our behavior, fall in line, shut our mouths, agree without rebuttal and abide by the “rules”. But the moment our anger, which is embedded in the fabric of our soul due to experiences and circumstances, bleeds out to be seen by others then we become perceived as animals and prodigals—barbarians even. We’re no longer useful or needed. The moment our humanity is seen, grace is rescinded and we’re sent back to our proverbial cages to “fix our attitude” and temper our anger or risk excommunication altogether. This seems to be the sentiments by many black men especially those trying to find refuge in predominantly white-led evangelical spaces. It’s the “good boys” who are presented and paraded because they mind their manners and abide by the “rules”. It’s not that they’re super gifted; it’s that they’re “safe”. This is the plight of many. There are so many “warriors” who’ve become emasculated and pusillanimous. And don’t we dare mention our situation. If we do then we’re just playing victims. So many silently conform while secretly desiring to be free. I played that game, and God knows I can’t play it anymore. God, help Your sons.
Love me. Anyone else? 🙋🏾‍♂️👀
😂That’s all I can do. Unfortunately, too many people decide how they want to treat you according to your profession. All they need to know is that I do my best, and that’s more than enough. 🤟🏾♾️

On today’s episode of THIS IS LIFE w/ Heather and Cornelius, I dive deeper into my struggle with depression and life expiration. I’ve had many people to inquire about that journey. The worst feeling is feeling like you’re alone and there’s nowhere to go for help. That’s the sentiment felt by many. When you’re the “strong one” it’s expected for you to be okay. And if you struggle then you’re “unfit”. Leaders aren’t supposed to show weakness in public. They’re meant to live like Naaman in the Bible. He was a great general who was praised publicly and known by the king, but he had a serious skin disease. Imagine that…………….he was a public hero yet he had a private problem. He covered his problem daily to perform for the people. The idea is that you could go to your pastor, but the feelings of abandonment and rejection only grows when s/he’s unresponsive or too busy. It would be great to go to therapy, but what happens when therapy becomes too expensive or when it becomes a time where you’re paying someone to be your friend😂 and just listen to you. As for me, I reached out to an in-patient treatment center that quoted me a starting rate of $25,000 for a minimum of 30 days. That’s affordable, right?! Then, there’s the reaching out to people who are quickly to accept your gifts but cannot stomach your humanity. You know what seems cheaper…………..but has latter consequences—escapism!? Jack Daniel’s and Jim Beam becomes trusted friends. Porn is used as a way to seek control and acceptance. It becomes the norm to just find something else to occupy our time and take our mind off everything—overeating, over indulging in entertainment, the gym, etc. Take a listen to my story. I pray it makes you feel less alone.

Never take constructive criticism from someone who has never constructed anything but an opinion. Notice how people who are actively involved in a personal transformative process don’t get involved in other people’s business. Why? Because they’re fully engaged on becoming the best version of themselves. It’s those who are unhealthy, internally wounded, secretly struggling, constantly hiding and filled with self-hatred that criticize. They’re great judges for everyone else and excellent attorneys for themselves. Their self-righteousness blinds then from seeing clearly, and they’ll never change anything but the mask they wear to hide just how broken they are within. Get serious about your own life. Laugh again. Find a good coach/mentor. Push yourself to your greatest potential. Get around people who challenge her you to be better. And deal with your own trauma while minding your own business. This is how you find God. It isn’t sitting in a building for 2 hours a week. It’s about engaging in an ongoing transformative process that includes a pain and struggle. That’s when change happens. That’s when progress can be seen. Although lonely, it’s necessary. 🤟🏾♾️🫶🏾
😂😂😂😂😂 love youuuuuuuuuu 🤟🏾🫶🏾♾️

Self-righteousness is the cancer of the Church. Because we’ve been trained to have a works-based doctrine that’s upheld by denominational idolatry where the words of men override the truth of God, we’ve become highly sanctimonious and judgmental. Most of the present-day church is filled with people who like a god they do not trust. Instead, it’s their works and intelligence they crown as king. They find scripture that justifies their humanity while condemning others for what they know not of. Sadly, those outside the church look on to see a community they would rather avoid. Self-righteousness is our enemy, and it’s prevailing. We care more about behavior modification than true authentic worship that’s filled with humanity. We save seats at our tables only for those we deem are worthy, but that wasn’t Jesus’ way. My journey has caused me to question what Jesus I claimed to serve. He spoke of paradox; the grey area; the in between—the space between completion of the Law and not getting rid of It. A space where humanity isn’t demonized and one’s personal journey is welcomed. It’s where we proclaim the beauty of being slayed and being tried because it produces the best in us. I’ve come to see how many people who are bound by their denominational doctrine are so bothered by the freedom of others. I get it though; their self-righteousness is blinding. They think their outward works are pleasing to God while they deny faith in Him by worshipping their actions. They think calling themselves worshippers makes them one. This is our sad reality. But I’ve come to see that the self-righteousness have yet to experience God in the midst of brokenness. They know nothing of humility. Their intelligence is their idol. And it makes sense why few find the narrow way. It’s for those who’ve denounced their self-righteousness to fully trust in God, which is SO DIFFICULT TO DO. I have nothing to boast of; to prove; to defend. My humanity and frailty proves my need for Jesus therefore I don’t have to practice false public perfection. I am who I am, and my road to New Jerusalem isn’t paved by my own merits. This is deliverance. Selah. 🤟🏾🫶🏾♾️

These words struck my heart with great force this morning when I read them. Mostly because I was a shame-distributer, but I called it “truth-telling.” It was my way of getting people back to “living right” and escaping “addiction”. It wasn’t until I accepted my own addictive behaviors and stopped glossing over them as if they didn’t exist that I saw just how futile my ways were. Though the messages were met with applause with shouts of “amen”, people left feeling buried under the weight of shame. There was no real deliverance in most cases; there was only modification in behavior, which enhanced our performance to appear better than we were.
-
While in AA, I was able to see just how much shame played a part in my life. Many of those men were so vulnerable and free. I couldn’t understand it. Many weren’t Christian. Some didn’t believe in anything. Why weren’t they hiding too? They kicked shame away. They had a freedom I had not yet experienced even though I was in church culture for most of my life. My immediate thought was…”this has to be wrong; they’re wrong! They need to be ashamed!” I noticed how deeply rooted it was in me. It was to the point that I constantly questioned my value; questioned my worth; questioned my existence. I saw God has a “loving” slave owner. Though I called Him Father, I treated Him like a master.
-
Too many men still live in shame. They’re “successful” yet filled with shame, which is why they need success, alcohol, pornography, food, etc to fill them. That’s the only time they find peace. There’s another way. Freedom is available. Let me show you!

-

It goes even further trying to convince ourselves that we are man enough. But I’ve come to know that there’s no gold at the end of that rainbow. There isn’t much in this life I haven’t done or accomplished in my 36 years of living. I was chasing wind—a fleeting success and false image. For me, the vulnerability of self-disclosure became a pathway towards freedom. It’s scary. It’s difficult. But it’s worth it. Let’s walk together. 🤟🏾♾️🫶🏾

Top 3 reasons people quit on their goals:
